## Abstract

The standard geometric treatment of polynomial root-finding fixes the horizontal axis and varies the curve. This paper proposes a dual viewpoint: fix the curve and vary the line. For any quadratic equation `ax² + bx + c = 0`, the substitution `M = −b/a`, `K = −c/a` yields a canonical rewriting `x² = Mx + K`, in which the
roots appear as x-coordinates of the intersection of the fixed parabola `y = x²`
and the variable line `y = Mx + K`. We call this the Diagonal Cutting method.

Within this framework, Vieta's formulas become geometric properties of the line,
the discriminant becomes a statement about intersection type, and complex roots
acquire a measurable geometric expression. The normalisation extends to polynomials
of arbitrary degree: fixing `y = xⁿ` and varying a polynomial of degree `n−1`
produces an intersection problem whose maximum solution count equals the degree —
an elementary geometric path to Bézout's theorem.

The algebraic content throughout is classical. The contribution is the reorientation,
and the structural observations that follow from it.